The paper also involves machine learning techniques, specifically DCNNs, which suggests that it could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. 

The paper's focus on identifying the ingredients necessary to close the gap in weakly supervised scenarios suggests that it could also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. 

The use of annotations and post-processing techniques in the paper suggests that it could also belong to the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category, which deals with natural language processing and related tasks. 

Finally, the paper's focus on state-of-the-art results and performance evaluation suggests that it could also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category, which deals with multimedia content analysis and retrieval.
